Comets.CatText: Comets are icy bodies that release gas or dust, originating from the outer regions of the Solar System.

Interstellar Objects.CatText: Interstellar Objects are objects that originate outside the Solar System, passing through it.

Oumuamua.Text: Oumuamua is the first known interstellar object detected passing through the Solar System.
Factoids: Oumuamua has a highly elongated shape.

Halley.Text: Halley's Comet is a short-period comet visible from Earth every 75-76 years.
Factoids: It is the only known short-period comet that is regularly visible to the naked eye from Earth.

Borrelly.Text: Comet Borrelly is a short-period comet that was visited by the Deep Space 1 spacecraft in 2001.
Factoids: Comet Borrelly has a nucleus approximately 8 kilometers long.
It has a dark surface with low reflectivity.

Tempel 1.Text: Comet Tempel 1 is a periodic comet that was the target of NASA's Deep Impact mission in 2005.
Factoids: Comet Tempel 1 has a nucleus approximately 6 kilometers in diameter.
The Deep Impact mission created a crater on the comet's surface to study its composition.

Wild 2.Text: Comet Wild 2 is a Jupiter-family comet that was visited by NASA's Stardust mission in 2004.
Factoids: Comet Wild 2 has a nucleus approximately 5 kilometers in diameter.
The Stardust mission collected samples of the comet's dust and returned them to Earth.

Hartley 2.Text: Comet Hartley 2 is a small, active comet that was visited by NASA's EPOXI mission in 2010.
Factoids: Comet Hartley 2 has a nucleus approximately 2.2 kilometers long.
The EPOXI mission observed the comet's activity and surface features.

Churyumov-Gerasimnko.Text: Comet 67P/Churyumov-Gerasimenko is a Jupiter-family comet that was the target of the European Space Agency's Rosetta mission.
Factoids: The comet has a distinctive rubber duck shape.
The Rosetta mission deployed the Philae lander to the comet's surface.
